Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.70) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.10. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.76 (S.E. = 2.03, p < .001, 95% CI [9.78, 17.73]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.038, 95% CI [4.14e-03, 0.15]; Std. beta = 0.27, 95% CI [0.01, 0.52])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 1.02, p = 0.899, 95% CI [-2.12, 1.86]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.52, 0.46])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.55, S.E. = 0.81, p = 0.502, 95% CI [-2.14, 1.05]; Std. beta = -0.13, 95% CI [-0.53, 0.26])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.29, S.E. = 1.21, p = 0.007, 95% CI [0.92, 5.67]; Std. beta = 0.81, 95% CI [0.23, 1.39])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
